snippet.textDisplay:
A video like this shows how much even the people who seem the happiest can be the most hurt..
Sean, the grown man we thought was the happiest man on this earth, had the saddest moments. And we all shake off when people say their fine most of the time because they seem happy, but what it matters is how they feel on the inside.


If you need help ever.
Find someone you love
A boyfriend, girlfriend, closest friend, parent.. teacher even.

As a bipolar, my depressive stages really get to me.
But my grandma was always open.
I told her about my thoughts
She was happy to help me
And i was happy to have her.

So the best advice from this. If sean is reading this or if someone else is.

Always find help. If you cant find help close by, call the suicide prevention hotline. They will always help you.
Coming from someone who has attempted suicide many times back then. You will feel terrible until you talk to someone who cares.
You have a family
You have your friends.
And no matter what, you will always have that one person that will be devastated if you died.

If sean read this, we love you sean, you were the start of the bright light of my life with your joy.
And we as your fans will do anything to help you.

And if you are just reading this, i love you too for just living
You are already winning in a war just reading this.
Dont give up
💚

snippet.textDisplay:
Hearing Jack talk so openly about his suicidal thoughts and depression has only made me love him even more as a person. It really shows that even the happiest and most cheerful people go through bad times.
I can relate on a personal level to his story; I, currently, am going through a really tough time. I'm stuck in a toxic relationship, my father passed away, and I just feel... alone. I ended up slipping into a period of self-harm because of it, and seriously considered suicide at times. But I'm slowly being able to find my way out of it, partly because of Jack. He has no idea, and he'll probably never see this comment, but his energy, his smile, and everything about him has shown me that it's possible to be happy, even in the worst of times. So, if you're reading this, Thank You, Jack.
If anyone reading this is also going through a tough time, just know that there will always be someone there for you. Trust me when I say that if you are gone, there will be people who miss you. Even if it doesn't seem like it. There's always someone who cares.
Stay strong <3

2016 was my worst year, but it ended up beginning the best progression of my life. Just starting college, I thought I knew what I was majoring in, and what I’d be doing in life. Then I failed a class, dropped my gpa to almost a 2.0, and lost my scholarships. I had to move back home because I couldn’t pay for the dorms anymore.

That summer, I decided to change my major to something I enjoyed, rather than something I’m just good at or smart enough to do. That brought me to teaching music. The first year of transition was tough, but I was brought in with open arms by people I can now call my best friends. Not to mention those who I met in the dorms stuck by my side through the whole thing as well.

Now it’s 2020, and I’m student teaching, and I have an interview for a real teaching job for next fall... my advice through this: stick with it, and change things if you aren’t happy. There’s a path out there, you just might not have found it yet

If someone says something to you, I think there's a specific way to think about it that can help, and it is sorta tied to the whole underdog/big dog dynamic. Do you HAVE to say something back? snippet.textDisplay:
Jack, btw, I think you're doing a great job as a Youtuber. I don't know you personally, but I'm glad that things are turning out better for you.

By the way, for anyone else going through difficult things like depression, anxiety, or otherwise, it sounds cliché, but you're not alone. You're not alone in your life, in your experiences, you're not alone. And if you think no one would care if you were gone, believe me when I say, people would care. So whatever is bugging you, talk about it. Scream about it. Write it out, do something. See someone. But don't bottle up your emotions. I've been there, and it is not a happy road, so let it out. I'm not a professional, but if you're able to, try to seek professional help. There are people who care. There are people who will help. And there are people who love you.
